# Contributions

## Branch Naming

```
<purpose>/<git-username>/<feature-name>
```

- **purpose**: `feature`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `poc`, etc.
- **name**: the author's name or alias
- **feature-name**: kebab-case description

Examples: `feature/jsmith/duck-ai-url-routing`, `fix/jsmith/bookmark-crash`

## Commit Messages

Use the imperative mood in the subject line (e.g. "Add feature X", not "Added feature X"). Keep the subject under 72 characters. Add a blank line before the body if more context is needed. Reference the Asana task URL in the body.

## PR body

Every PR must use the exact format from `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`. This applies when creating PRs via `gh`, `gt submit`, or the GT MCP — always populate the body from this template:

```
Task/Issue URL: <Asana task URL>

### Description

### Steps to test this PR

_Feature 1_
- [ ]
- [ ]

### UI changes
| Before  | After |
| ------ | ----- |
!(Upload before screenshot)|(Upload after screenshot)|
```

**Task/Issue URL** — Plain text line (no heading), link to the Asana task.

**Description** — A short summary of what changed and why.

**Steps to test this PR** — Reviewer-facing steps per scenario. Be specific enough that someone unfamiliar with the code can follow them.

**UI changes** — Before/After screenshots or recordings. Omit the table and write "N/A" only for pure logic/backend changes with no visual impact.

## Stacked PRs (Graphite)

We use Graphite for stacked pull requests. When asked to build a complete feature, plan a stack of PRs following the ordering below before writing any code. For any other task, follow the engineer's instructions on how to structure the work. Each PR in the stack must build and pass `./gradlew jvm_checks` independently.

### Stack ordering

Structure the stack around the evolution of the work, not the module layout:

1. **Feature flag** (if needed) — remote feature toggle gating the new behaviour
2. **Implementation** (one or more PRs) — the feature itself, including UI, logic, and unit tests; split into multiple PRs if the feature is large enough to benefit from independent review
3. **Pixels** — analytics events for the feature
4. **Translations** — any new strings added for the feature

### Creating stacked PRs

If the GT MCP is available, use it to create and submit stacked PRs. Otherwise, create branches and PRs manually using `gh`. In both cases, each PR body must follow the template in the **PR body** section above.